<TEXT>
when house speaker jim wright sent out a 
questionnaire on the pay raise issue to his colleagues last week 
one came back with a cryptic note sam rayburn would not have sent 
out a survey like this 
the reference to fellow texan rayburn considered among the 
strongest house speakers in the century was a pointed jab at wright 
for failing to take command on the controversial issue and instead 
attempting to spread the blame by seeking the opinions of his 
colleagues 
there were four who wrote on the survey something to the effect 
that this is a bum idea wright conceded to reporters as he 
handed out the results of his poll last week but he contended many 
more members were glad to be consulted on how to handle the 
recommended 51 percent pay hike 
wrights venture into the polling business an apparent attempt 
to demonstrate that he was acting on behalf of a majority of house 
members to engineer a salary increase appeared to have backfired in 
several ways 
for one the speaker failed to consult even his top leadership 
team before sending out the 12question survey form 
the leaders in turn were left scrambling to distance themselves 
from what they clearly considered a dubious idea 
some senior democrats were bitter about the move this has 
permanently hurt wright said one speaking only on condition of 
anonymity 
in addition the confidential survey was sharply at odds with the 
outcomes of several public surveys conducted by the news media and 
interest groups 
wright said of 326 house members responding privately to his 
survey 57 percent did not want to vote on the pay raise before it 
goes into effect at midnight tuesday 
but when the associated press queried 105 lawmakers 88 percent 
said they did want to vote before the deadline in an informal poll 
of 278 members by the selfdescribed consumer group public citizen 
265 61 percent of the house said on the record that they wanted 
a vote 
somebodys not telling the truth said public citizens ralph 
nader an outspoken pay raise critic for the speaker to expose 
members to a charge of lying is a very serious case of leadership 
run amok 
wright intended the survey to bolster his strategy of letting the 
raise go into effect then holding a vote to roll it back to 30 
percent but it instead showed the speaker could fall short of the 
twothirds majority needed for a rollback under the expedited 
process he chose for bringing the issue to the floor 
what the results did show was deep division among house members 
over the entire issue of congressional pay and how it is set and 
inconsistency between the answers to some questions for example 
fiftysix percent favored and 44 percent opposed the process 
under which pay levels for lawmakers and top officials are 
recommended by an independent commission proposed by the president 
and put in effect automatically unless both houses vote to cancel 
them 
on the question of whether they would vote against any effort 
to rescind the raise entirely 49 percent said yes and 46 percent 
said no 
asked if the 50 percent raise for congress and similar 
increases for other top government jobs were fair and proper 54 
percent said yes but asked more specifically about the amount of 
the increases 56 percent said they were too high 
a majority 54 percent opposed a vote before wednesday on 
banning honoraria such as fees for speaking before lobbying groups 
and limiting the raise to 30 percent but after wednesday and 
following an honoraria ban 61 percent favored rolling back the pay 
raise to 30 percent 
only on one question were sentiments near unanimous 98 percent 
said they would vote to ban honoraria if the pay raise goes into 
effect 
the survey has put the heat on everybody and it isnt going to 
go away said rep tim penny of minnesota one of the few 
democrats willing to criticize the speaker publicly this issue is 
going to leave a bad taste in the mouths of a lot of members and 
eventually thats got to add up sooner or later the good will is 
going to be gone 
some lawmakers observed that wright came into the fray over pay 
carrying heavy political baggage from two continuing house ethics 
committee investigations into his conduct one case involving 
allegations the speaker abused his office while majority leader for 
financial gain is expected to be resolved late this month 
whatever the outcome of that inquiry wright will likely face 
another public pummeling led by his chief accuser rep newt 
gingrich rga and the fallout from the survey could hurt said 
one prominent house democrat 
in a matter of weeks hell be asking these same people to 
stand up for him against gingrich said the lawmaker 
