<TEXT>
when levi strauss amp co announced last week it 
would close a denim jacket plant in tennessee it gave 140 workers 
90 days paid notice 
it was a better cushion than most workers have been getting when 
plants close down 
levi strauss was following voluntary policies in place since 
1984 guaranteeing workers advance notice of pending plant closings 
notice of plant closings and largescale layoffs however is now 
the law 
plant closing legislation passed by congress last year took full 
effect saturday with business and labor still debating its impact 
and both sides predicting a flood of lawsuits 
the companies are mystified at how complicated this law really 
is said renee reymond of the national association of 
manufacturers the labor attorneys certainly are poised and ready 
for business 
supporters say the law will not hurt business and gives workers a 
time to prepare for job loss federal figures show 64 percent of the 
nearly 2 million workers idled annually receive no notice 
opponents maintain the law represents a threat to industry 
the threat is one of government fines lawsuits back pay and 
benefits expenses loss of market image and costly training and 
adjustment problems the virginia employers association declared 
recently 
thenpresident reagan allowed the measure to become law in august 
without his signature despite having earlier called it a ticking 
time bomb in the back seat of any mediumsized or larger company 
pressure from then presidential candidate george bush was said to 
have influenced reagan 
on capitol hill supporters of the concept still say it was long 
overdue 
the chicken littles have been proven wrong again said sen 
edward m kennedy dmass the sky did not fall enactment of this 
law was a triumph of reason over ideology and american workers will 
now receive the notice they deserve 
provisions of the law call for it to take effect saturday but 
some employers have started early on the theory that courts may 
eventually hold that shutdowns up to 60 days beforehand were covered 
lehigh structural steel co of allentown pa for example 
announced jan 24 that its 184 employees would be laid off after 
current orders are filled president r leslie mullen said in a 
telephone interview last week that the company was observing the 
60day notice period 
nobody can seem to tell us what the law is so were being 
safe mullen said 
a random survey of a dozen companies that have announced 
shutdowns or major layoffs in the past two months found that nearly 
all had given their workers at least 60 days notice most because 
of company policies in place before the law was passed 
for example 
pillsbury co said last week it would close a pizza plant in 
missouri and a potato flake plant in north dakota idling 334 
workers who got 60 days notice 
atampt recently announced plans to close two facilities in the 
washington dc area one with 500 workers the other 130 many 
are being offered jobs elesewhere in the company and atampt has a 
policy of giving a minimum 90day notice spokesman don griffith 
said 
mack trucks inc five weeks ago announced it was laying off 300 
workers at its macungie pa assembly plant but since has said 
only about half that many would lose their jobs 
mack spokeswoman debbie morgan said the union workers had been 
told of the initial layoff plans several months before the 
announcement 
our policy has been that were not going to wait until february 
to be in compliance she said we decided to treat it as if it 
was in effect immediately 
but about 130 workers at a microwave plant in sioux falls sd 
who lost their jobs friday got only one week notice the layoffs do 
not appear to be covered by the law even under the liberal 
interpretation of its effective date 
the law requires advance notice of plant closings by employers 
with at least 100 fulltime workers if the shutdown will cost 50 or 
more of those employees their jobs in the case of layoffs notices 
are required if the number of affected workers totals 33 percent of 
the companys employees or 500 whichever figure is lower 
in sioux falls microwave products of america began the year with 
about 650 workers at its plant and in january laid off 155 that 
left the company with about 495 workers by laying off 130 workers 
the company fell about 35 short of the 33 percent threshold 
it was reviewed company spokesman gordon taylor said when 
asked about the plant closing law he said the companys position 
was that the law did not carry weight until after saturday and also 
noted that regardless of the effective date the layoffs did not meet 
the threshold 
