the only big difference between this auction and the previous two 
is that it includes the 30year bond which was on hiatus because 
congress had failed to raise the ceiling on issuance of longterm 
debt congress finally passed new legislation before it adjourned 
last year 
while there were few surprises in the size of the upcoming sale 
economists appeared divided on how well it might go in the wake of 
the latest economic data 
adding pressure to the credit markets was the governments 
january unemployment report which pointed to continued strength in 
the economy along with the possibility of higher inflation 
the report released friday showed that the nations jobless 
rate inched up to 54 percent in january from 53 percent at the end 
of the year but despite the slight increase 408000 new jobs were 
created last month and that was far more than most economists had 
predicted 
we believe the employment data is extremely negative said 
william v sullivan director of money market research for dean 
witter reynolds inc it increases the pressures for the fed to 
tighten credit 
the federal reserve has indicated repeatedly that it will push 
for higher interest rates to keep inflation in check thereby making 
borrowing more expensive and slowing down economic growth 
sullivan and several other analysts predict that interest rates 
will be on the rise going into the upcoming auction 
we dont think the current yield level reflects the underlying 
fundamentals in the us economy he said 
the upward slant in rates will put pressure on the treasury to 
make the yields of its new bonds and notes high enough to attract 
domestic and foreign money 
one saving grace though is the fact that the dollar has 
remained strong in foreign exchange 
the foreign exchange market is definitely a plus for the 
treasury auction said carol a stone a senior economist for 
nomura securities international inc i would say there will be 
good foreign participation 
a rising dollar is seen as good news for foreigners because it 
means they are likely to earn more on their dollardenominated 
investments 
proceeds of the upcoming treasury auction will be used toward 
raising about 137 billion in cash and redeeming 151 billion in 
old obligations which make up part of the 28 trillion national 
debt 
the sale will begin on tuesday with 975 billion worth of 
threeyear notes followed by 95 billion in 10year securities on 
wednesday and 95 billion thursday 
</TEXT>
